mps, and their story is little known to English-language readers. Because of the length of his internment, his decision to write his book as fiction, and his staggering powers of observation and recollection, Amat-Piniella’s portrayal of life in the camps is unmatched in scope and detail. It is also a compelling study of three powerful ideological movements at work at the time: anarchism, communism, and fascism, all within the desperate and brutal world of the camps. “My book does not seek to deepen wounds or differences, but to unite people before cruelty,” said Amat-Piniella. This is an essential text as we ponder the twentieth century and its meaning to us today. This edition includes a new preface, annotations, and a translators’ note.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPrisoners of warzGermanyvFiction. 0aPrisoners of warzSpainvFiction. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConcentration campszAustriazMauthausenvFiction. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPrisoners and prisons, GermanvFiction. 4aFiction: Fiction In Translation. 4aHistory: Holocaust Studies. 4aLanguage Arts & Disciplines: Translation. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aFinley, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarín-Dòmine, Marta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709740uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112018040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771120180423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771120180/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles